HW-3 Penalized Regression Approaches¶

Main purpose of this homework is to forecast the tomorrow’s hourly electricity consumption of Turkey. For this pupose the data from 1st of January, 2016 till the 1st of December, 2020 is used. Alternative strategies to model the consumption prediction are used to predict the tomorrow’s hourly electricity consumption, then these approaches are compared by using mean absolute percentage error (MAPE).¶

Task A¶

In this task, 168 and 48 hours ago consumption values are used to predict next day’s consumption.¶

    data_test$Lag48[i-len] = data$Consumption..MWh.[i-48]
    data_test$Lag168[i-len] = data$Consumption..MWh.[i-168]

    data_test$error_48[i] = abs((data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i]- data_test$Lag48[i])/ data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i])*100
    data_test$error_168[i] = abs((data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i]- data_test$Lag168[i])/ data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i])*100
}
#Hourly mape values are calculated
data_test$Hour = as.numeric(str_sub(data_test$Hour,1,2))
mape_Lag48_hour = c()
mape_Lag168_hour =c()
for (i in 0:23){
    new_data_a = data_test %>% filter(Hour == i)
    mape_Lag48_hour[(i+1)] = mean(new_data_a$error_48)
    mape_Lag168_hour[(i+1)] = mean(new_data_a$error_168)
}

Task B¶

In this task, data is presented as long format then linear regression model is used with two features (Lag48 and Lag168) and an intercept. Then mape values are calculated.¶

In [9]:
#First 168 days are elimineted to be able to use the data 168 days ago
leng_train = nrow(data_train)
data_long = data_train[169:leng_train,]
new_length =nrow(data_long)
#Lag48 and Lag168 are calculated for training data
for (i in 1:new_length){
    data_long$Lag48[i] = data_train$Consumption..MWh.[i+168-48]
    data_long$Lag168[i] = data_train$Consumption..MWh.[i]
}
#Linear regression is applied with lm function
model = lm(Consumption..MWh.~ Lag48 + Lag168, data_long)

#Consumption data is predicted for test period
data_test$prediction = predict.lm(model,data_test)
test_long = nrow(data_test)

#Absolute percentage error is calculated to predict the mape value
for (i in 1:test_long){
    data_test$error[i] = abs((data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i]- data_test$prediction[i])/ data_test$Consumption..MWh.[i])*100
}
#Hourly mape values are calculated
mape_linear_hour = c()
for (i in 0:23){
    new_data_b = data_test %>% filter(Hour == i)
    mape_linear_hour[(i+1)] = mean(new_data_b$error)
}

Task D¶

Data is presented as wide format and prediction model is built by 48 features (hourly consumption from two days ago and last week’s hourly consumption) and penalized regression approaches with a 10-fold cross-validation.¶

In [12]:
#training data conversion
data_d = data_long
data_d$Date <- as.Date(data_d$Date,"%d.%m.%Y")
Lag_168_hour = dcast(data_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Lag168" )
colnames(Lag_168_hour) <- c("Date",paste0("Lag168_hour_", 0:23))
Lag_48_hour = dcast(data_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Lag48" )
colnames(Lag_48_hour) <- c("Date",paste0("Lag48_hour_", 0:23))
Cons_hour = dcast(data_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Consumption..MWh." )
colnames(Cons_hour) <- c("Date",paste0("Consumption_hour_", 0:23))
day_hour_data_train = cbind(Lag_168_hour, Lag_48_hour[,2:25], Cons_hour[,2:25])
#test data conversion
data_test_d = data_test
data_test_d$Date <- as.Date(data_test_d$Date,"%d.%m.%Y")
Lag_168_hour_2 = dcast(data_test_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Lag168" )
colnames(Lag_168_hour_2) <- c("Date",paste0("Lag168_hour_", 0:23))
Lag_48_hour_2 = dcast(data_test_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Lag48" )
colnames(Lag_48_hour_2) <- c("Date",paste0("Lag48_hour_", 0:23))
Cons_hour_2 = dcast(data_test_d, Date ~ Hour, sum, value.var = "Consumption..MWh." )
colnames(Cons_hour_2) <- c("Date",paste0("Consumption_hour_", 0:23))
day_hour_data_test = cbind(Lag_168_hour_2, Lag_48_hour_2[,2:25], Cons_hour_2[,2:25])
#combining datas
day_hour_data = rbind(day_hour_data_train, day_hour_data_test)
In [13]:
#Matrix and vectors are defined
x_train = day_hour_data_train[,2:49]
x_test = day_hour_data_test[,2:49]
x_train =  as.matrix(x_train)
x_test =  as.matrix(x_test)
lasso = c()
pred = matrix(0,31,24)
error = matrix(0,31,24)
mape_d = c()
lasso_coef = c()
lasso_model=c()
model_24hour = c()
A=c()
coeff_lasso = c()
#coeff_lasso = matrix(0,49,24)
for (i in 1:24){
    set.seed(621)
    #consumtion data for each hour is equalized to y for training data and y_test for test data
    y = day_hour_data_train[,49+i]
    y_test = day_hour_data_test[,49+i]
    y = as.matrix(y)
    #glmnet function is used to obtain model
    lasso_model = cv.glmnet(x_train , y  , type.measure="mse", family="gaussian", nfolds = 10)
    hour = paste0(i-1,":00")
    plot(lasso_model, sub=substitute(paste('Hour =', hour)))
    title("Lasso Model",adj = 0.5, line = 2)     
    #lambda is selected as lambda.1se
    lambdax = lasso_model$lambda.1se
    best_lasso = glmnet(x_train , y  , alpha =1, lambda = lambdax)
    #prediction is made for test data and mape values are calculated
    lasso = predict(best_lasso,  s=lambdax, newx = x_test)
    len_x_test =nrow(x_test)
    lasso_coef$lambda_1se[i] = lasso_model$lambda.1se
    lasso_coef$lambda_min[i] = lasso_model$lambda.min
    if (i==1){
        coeff_lasso = coefficients(lasso_model)
    }
    coeff_lasso = cbind(coeff_lasso, coefficients(lasso_model))
    #A = coefficients(lasso_model)
    #coeff_lasso[,i] = A[,1]
    for (j in 1:len_x_test){
        pred[j,i] = lasso[j,1]
        error[j,i] = abs((y_test[j]-pred[j,i])/y_test[j])*100
    }
    mape_d[i] = mean(error[,i])  
}

When we look at the mean-squared error vs log(lambda) graph, it can be deduced that in lower lambda values, the variance is much lower than the higher lambda values. For this reason, it is prefered to use lambda.min and lambda.1se to minimize the mean squared error and variance. When we look at the 24 graph for each hour, it can be concluded that they have similar profile.¶

Lag48 = mape_Lag48_hour
Lag168 = mape_Lag168_hour
Linear_reg = mape_linear_hour
Hourly_lin = mape_3nd
Lasso = mape_d
results = cbind(Lag48, Lag168, Linear_reg, Hourly_lin, Lasso)
results = data.frame(results)
boxplot(results,main="MAPE Comparison",
xlab="Regression Model",
ylab="MAPE",
col=topo.colors(5),
border="brown"
)

Mape values obtained by the model with Lasso approach for each hour are the lowest mape values calculated in this homework. Also, the variance of mape values in this approach is small. For this reason, it can be concluded that the Lasso approach is best way to predict the electiricity consumption for the next day beyond the methods used in this homework. Second best method is the method in which 168 hours ago consumption values used as our naïve approaches to predict next day’s consumption. Mean value of mape calculations of this approach is also lower and variance of mape values is the smallest among the other methods. The mape values calculated by linear regression method in part b has third lowest mean value, however its variance is higher than the hourly linear regression method. The worst method is the model in which 48 hours ago consumption values used as our naïve approaches to predict next day’s consumption, because its mean value of mape calculations are highest and its variance is very high.¶
